ilt with Apple clang version 17.0.0 (clang-1700.6.3.2)\n  configuration: --prefix=/opt/homebrew/Cellar/ffmpeg/8.0.1_4 --enable-shared --enable-pthreads --enable-version3 --cc=clang --host-cflags= --host-ldflags= --enable-ffplay --enable-gpl --enable-libsvtav1 --enable-libopus --enable-libx264 --enable-libmp3lame --enable-libdav1d --enable-libvpx --enable-libx265 --enable-openssl --enable-videotoolbox --enable-audiotoolbox --enable-neon\n  libavutil      60.  8.100 / 60.  8.100\n  libavcodec     62. 11.100 / 62. 11.100\n  libavformat    62.  3.100 / 62.  3.100\n  libavdevice    62.  1.100 / 62.  1.100\n  libavfilter    11.  4.100 / 11.  4.100\n  libswscale      9.  1.100 /  9.  1.100\n  libswresample   6.  1.100 /  6.  1.100\n[aist#0:0/pcm_s16be @ 0x94ec14180] Guessed Channel Layout: mono\nInput #0, aiff, from '/tmp/section1_part2.aiff':\n  Duration: 00:01:40.88, start: 0.000000, bitrate: 353 kb/s\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: pcm_s16be (twos / 0x736F7774), 22050 Hz, mono, s16, 352 kb/s\nStream mapping:\n  Stream #0:0 -> #0:0 (pcm_s16be (native) -> mp3 (libmp3lame))\nPress [q] to stop, [?] for help\nOutput #0, mp3, to '/tmp/section1_part2.mp3':\n  Metadata:\n    TSSE            : Lavf62.3.100\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: mp3, 22050 Hz, mono, s16p\n    Metadata:\n      encoder         : Lavc62.11.100 libmp3lame\n[out#0/mp3 @ 0x94f024180] video:0KiB audio:394KiB subtitle:0KiB other streams:0KiB global headers:0KiB muxing overhead: 0.055975%\nsize=     395KiB time=00:01:40.88 bitrate=  32.0kbits/s speed= 351x elapsed=0:00:00.28    \nPart 2 done","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777739564946}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f971e4e","parentId":"75b887d2","timestamp":"2026-05-02T16:32:51.400Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, now parts 3, 4, and 5.\n","thinkingSignature":"1d690036bb6a2542867a622a44ed9b129b29094d892c57e2ef875d20da186484"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qrin05l0emcw_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"say -v 'Samantha' \"What OpenClaw Actually Does\n\nHere's what that means in practice:\n\nIt creates and manages files. Instead of just opening folders, OpenClaw builds them, organizes them, renames them, cleans them up. It handles my storage intelligently instead of me manually dragging files around. I tell it what I want, it figures out where it goes.\n\nIt runs automations. Things that used to take manual effort every single day — like a morning briefing on what's ahead, what's coming up, what the weather looks like — now happen automatically. I wake up and the information is already there. No prompting, no asking. It just happens.\n\nIt builds things without code. This one's huge. I don't know how to code, I still don't. But OpenClaw can help me create apps — personal tools for myself or even public ones people can actually use. That's not something most people can do without hiring a developer.\n\nIt's always on. Unlike ChatGPT where you open it, ask a question, close it, OpenClaw lives in your system. It monitors, it reminds, it checks, it coordinates throughout the day, not just when you talk to it.\n\nIt's saved me time and reduced my mental load. Things I used to have to track in my head — appointments, follow-ups, reminders, daily check-ins — OpenClaw handles that. I free up brain space for the things I actually want to focus on.\" -o /tmp/section1_part3.aiff && ffmpeg -i /tmp/section1_part3.aiff /tmp/section1_part3.mp3 -y && cp /tmp/section1_part3.mp3 ~/.openclaw/media/section1_part3.mp3 && echo \"Part 3 done\"","timeout":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1185,"output":409,"cacheRead":90976,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":92570,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777739564948,"responseId":"06455a2d5c88871601d2a707135252db"}}
{"type":"message","id":"88ff2c97","parentId":"1f971e4e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T16:32:52.856Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_qrin05l0emcw_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ffmpeg version 8.0.1 Copyright (c) 2000-2025 the FFmpeg developers\n  built with Apple clang version 17.0.0 (clang-1700.6.3.2)\n  configuration: --prefix=/opt/homebrew/Cellar/ffmpeg/8.0.1_4 --enable-shared --enable-pthreads --enable-version3 --cc=clang --host-cflags= --host-ldflags= --enable-ffplay --enable-gpl --enable-libsvtav1 --enable-libopus --enable-libx264 --enable-libmp3lame --enable-libdav1d --enable-libvpx --enable-libx265 --enable-openssl --enable-videotoolbox --enable-audiotoolbox --enable-neon\n  libavutil      60.  8.100 / 60.  8.100\n  libavcodec     62. 11.100 / 62. 11.100\n  libavformat    62.  3.100 / 62.  3.100\n  libavdevice    62.  1.100 / 62.  1.100\n  libavfilter    11.  4.100 / 11.  4.100\n  libswscale      9.  1.100 /  9.  1.100\n  libswresample   6.  1.100 /  6.  1.100\n[aist#0:0/pcm_s16be @ 0xc26c14180] Guessed Channel Layout: mono\nInput #0, aiff, from '/tmp/section1_part3.aiff':\n  Duration: 00:01:22.18, start: 0.000000, bitrate: 353 kb/s\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: pcm_s16be (twos / 0x736F7774), 22050 Hz, mono, s16, 352 kb/s\nStream mapping:\n  Stream #0:0 -> #0:0 (pcm_s16be (native) -> mp3 (libmp3lame))\nPress [q] to stop, [?] for help\nOutput #0, mp3, to '/tmp/section1_part3.mp3':\n  Metadata:\n    TSSE            : Lavf62.3.100\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: mp3, 22050 Hz, mono, s16p\n    Metadata:\n      encoder         : Lavc62.11.100 libmp3lame\n[out#0/mp3 @ 0xc270046c0] video:0KiB audio:321KiB subtitle:0KiB other streams:0KiB global headers:0KiB muxing overhead: 0.068707%\nsize=     321KiB time=00:01:22.17 bitrate=  32.0kbits/s speed= 357x elapsed=0:00:00.22    \nPart 3 done"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1360,"aggregated":"ffmpeg version 8.0.1 Copyright (c) 2000-2025 the FFmpeg developers\n  built with Apple clang version 17.0.0 (clang-1700.6.3.2)\n  configuration: --prefix=/opt/homebrew/Cellar/ffmpeg/8.0.1_4 --enable-shared --enable-pthreads --enable-version3 --cc=clang --host-cflags= --host-ldflags= --enable-ffplay --enable-gpl --enable-libsvtav1 --enable-libopus --enable-libx264 --enable-libmp3lame --enable-libdav1d --enable-libvpx --enable-libx265 --enable-openssl --enable-videotoolbox --enable-audiotoolbox --enable-neon\n  libavutil      60.  8.100 / 60.  8.100\n  libavcodec     62. 11.100 / 62. 11.100\n  libavformat    62.  3.100 / 62.  3.100\n  libavdevice    62.  1.100 / 62.  1.100\n  libavfilter    11.  4.100 / 11.  4.100\n  libswscale      9.  1.100 /  9.  1.100\n  libswresample   6.  1.100 /  6.  1.100\n[aist#0:0/pcm_s16be @ 0xc26c14180] Guessed Channel Layout: mono\nInput #0, aiff, from '/tmp/section1_part3.aiff':\n  Duration: 00:01:22.18, start: 0.000000, bitrate: 353 kb/s\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: pcm_s16be (twos / 0x736F7774), 22050 Hz, mono, s16, 352 kb/s\nStream mapping:\n  Stream #0:0 -> #0:0 (pcm_s16be (native) -> mp3 (libmp3lame))\nPress [q] to stop, [?] for help\nOutput #0, mp3, to '/tmp/section1_part3.mp3':\n  Metadata:\n    TSSE            : Lavf62.3.100\n  Stream #0:0: Audio: mp3, 22050 Hz, mono, s16p\n    Metadata:\n      encoder         : Lavc62.11.100 libmp3lame\n[out#0/mp3 @ 0xc270046c0] video:0KiB audio:321KiB subtitle:0KiB other streams:0KiB global headers:0KiB muxing overhead: 0.068707%\nsize=     321KiB time=00:01:22.17 bitrate=  32.0kbits/s speed= 357x elapsed=0:00:00.22    \nPart 3 done","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777739572856}}
{"type":"message","id":"ae4684b7","parentId":"88ff2c97","timestamp":"2026-05-02T16:33:03.320Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, now let me do part 4 - What OpenClaw is NOT, My Agent Team, and What Surprised Me Most.","thinkingSignature":"41fa549c27762e467986cb2c4428b6a69fa4060a9ad5c07263221b73e78d0a06"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2exqzl0rr1xc_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"say -v 'Samantha' \"What OpenClaw is NOT\n\nI want to be straight with you here, because there's a lot of hype around AI tools right now.\n\nOpenClaw is not magic. It won't read your mind. It won't do things you haven't taught it to do. And it won't work perfectly the first time you set it up — there's a learning curve.\n\nIt's also not a chatbot you just 'talk to sometimes.' The real power comes from building automations and workflows that run on their own. The more you put into setting it up and teaching it, the more you get out of it.\n\nAnd honestly? It's not for everyone. If you don't want to spend any time learning how it works, you'll get frustrated. But if you're willing to spend even a little time building your setup, it's one of the most powerful tools you can have.\n\nMy Agent Team — A Real Example of What OpenClaw Can Do\n\nOne of the most powerful things about OpenClaw is the agent system. I didn't know how to code. I didn't have a technical background. But I built a team — entirely with OpenClaw — that runs alongside me every day.\n\nHere's my team: Dean coordinates everything and routes work to the right specialist. Emmy handles my emails. Inbox zero, important messages flagged. Finn manages my finances. Tracks bills, monitors my cash position. Agent X runs my X and Twitter. Posts, engages, keeps my presence active. YoYo manages my YouTube. Content ideas, uploads, channel management. Rex does deep research. Cody builds tools and apps. DJ handles music and audio needs. Reese helps in the kitchen with recipes and meal planning.\n\nEvery morning, Dean sends me a briefing. Every evening, I get a financial update. When I need something, I tell Dean and he routes it to whoever needs to handle it.\n\nThis isn't science fiction. It's not something I hired a developer to build. I set it up myself, piece by piece, using OpenClaw.\n\nAnd that's what this guide is really about — showing you what's possible so you can build your own version.\n\nWhat Surprised Me Most\n\nI'll be real — there were things I didn't expect.\n\nThat I could actually build apps. I didn't know how to code. I still don't. But I built a working app from scratch using OpenClaw. That still trips me out a little.\n\nThat it actually remembered things. Not just in the moment, but long-term. Files I created months ago, decisions I made, preferences I forgot I even had — it all stuck around.\n\nHow much clearer my head felt. This sounds weird, but once I had a system that could track things for me, my brain stopped trying to hold it all. That mental clarity is harder to quantify but just as valuable as the time it saves.\n\nHow fast it became second nature. Within a week, I wasn't thinking about it anymore. I was just asking. 'Hey, add that to the list.' 'Remind me about that tomorrow.' It just worked.\n\nIf any of that resonated with you — keep reading. This guide is designed to get you exactly there.\" -o /tmp/section1_part4.aiff && ffmpeg -i /tmp/section1_part4.aiff /tmp/section1_part4.mp3 -y && cp /tmp/section1_part4.mp3 ~/.openclaw/media/section1_part4.mp3 && echo \"Part 4 done\"","timeout":90}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1108,"output":765,"cacheRead":92128,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":94001,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777739572858,"responseId":"06455a34f666637314b54002bb25e373"}}
